const char * pathToDataPtr:

1/ Your variable is not meant to be modified, so it should be a const
2/ Pointers end with Ptr by convention in Legato

I would start building a structure for all that if I were you:

typedef struct {
   le_avdata_DataType_t dataType;  ///< Type of data
   const char * configTreePathPtr; ///< Path to data in the configTree.
   const char * resourcePathPtr;   ///< Path to the resource when accessed from AVC.
} ConfigEntry_t;

const ConfigEntry_t ConfigEntries[] = {
   { LE_AVDATA_DATA_TYPE_STRING,
     CONFIG_TREE_URL,
     CONFIG_TREE_URL },
   { LE_AVDATA_DATA_TYPE_INT,
     CONFIG_TREE_POLLINGINTERVALSEC,
     CONFIG_TREE_POLLINGINTERVALSEC },
   /* ... insert other entries here ... */
};

Based on the entries in that database, you should be able to replace pretty much everything hardcoded in this file by a for loop on this table.

Use something like:
for(int i=0; i < NUM_ARRAY_MEMBERS(ConfigEntries); i++)
{
   const ConfigEntry_t * configEntryPtr = &ConfigEntries[i];
   ...
}

